A: Time series¶

Background information¶

Aim to peak emissions at 65 million tons of CO2equivalent (MtCO2e) around 2030 and halve our emissions from its peak to 33 MtCO2e by 2050, with a view to achieving net zero emissions as soon as viable in the second half of the century.

def plot_percentage_change_bar(title,consumption):
    # Plot the bar graph
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 6))
    plt.bar(res['Month'], res[consumption], color=res[consumption].apply(lambda x: 'red' if x > 0 else 'green'))

    # Add labels and title
    plt.xlabel('Months')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage Change')
    plt.title(title)

    # Add percentage values above bars
    for i, v in enumerate(res[consumption]):
        plt.text(i, v, f"{v:.1f}%", ha='center', va='bottom', fontweight='bold')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Assuming you have separate resFrames for gas, water, and electricity consumption changes
# gas_res, water_res, electricity_res are assumed to be resFrames with columns 'Month' and '%Change (gas)', '%Change (water)', '%Change (electricity)' respectively.

plot_percentage_change_bar('Percentage Change in Gas Consumption in 2022', '%Change (gas)')
plot_percentage_change_bar('Percentage Change in Water Consumption in 2022', '%Change (water)')
plot_percentage_change_bar('Percentage Change in Electricity Consumption in 2022', '%Change (electricity)')

The data is most likely not from a country with four seasons as there is no increase in percentage change during the winter seasons December to Feburary.

Generally there are more occurance of increase in consumption for gas and electricity especially during the period between May and July whereas for water there are more dips in consumption in periods of 3 consecutively months.

The increase in gas and electricity consumption during May to July might due to more people switiching on the air-conditioner in higher temperatures during these months.

Stationary check¶

In [15]:
# Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
def fuller(col):
    result1 = adfuller(df[col])
    return print(col,'p-value is ',result1[1])

# print('Gas consumption p-value:',result1[1])

fuller('Gas Consumption (tons)')
fuller('Electricity Consumption (MWh)')
fuller('Water Consumption (tons)')

Gas Consumption (tons) p-value is  0.01081065170706051
Electricity Consumption (MWh) p-value is  0.18621802300336632
Water Consumption (tons) p-value is  8.984549388336973e-05

P-value <= 0.05: Reject the null hypothesis (H0), the gas and water data does not have a unit root and is stationary.

P-value > 0.05: Fail to reject the null hypothesis (H0), the electricity has a unit root and is non-stationary

Differencing¶

Differencing technique helps to remove the trend and seasonality from time series data by subtracting the current value from the previous to transform series into stationarity

In [16]:
#for electricity
In [17]:
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.tools import diff
# perform differencing operation

df_diff = electricity.diff(periods=1)

# Perform Augmented Dickey-Fuller test on the original and differenced time series
resultt = adfuller(electricity)
result2 = adfuller(df_diff.dropna())  # Drop the first two NaN values due to differencing

# Print p-values
print('Electricity Consumption (MWh) before differencing p-value: %f' % resultt[1])
print('Electricity Consumption (MWh) after differencing p-value: %f' % result2[1])

# Plot the original time series and the differenced time series side by side
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 4))
electricity.plot(ax=ax[0])
df_diff.plot(ax=ax[1])
ax[0].set_title('Electricity Consumption (MWh) Time Series Before Differencing')
ax[1].set_title('Electricity Consumption (MWh) Time Series After Differencing')
plt.show()

Electricity Consumption (MWh) before differencing p-value: 0.186218
Electricity Consumption (MWh) after differencing p-value: 0.000000

P value has become less than 0.05, hence after differencing the data became stationary

Decomposition¶

Models are additive as the graphs do not show increasing or decreasing frequency and/or amplitude over time.

Additive Model : Data has same width and height of the seasonal patterns or peaks. Trend of the data is linear.

Multiplicative Model : Data has increasing / decreasing width and height of the seasonal patterns or peaks. Trend of the data is non-linear.

ARIMA function¶

p : This value is determined from partial autocorrelation graph

d : This value is determined from the amount of times differencing operation is carried out to make the time series stationary.

q : This value is determined from the autocorrelation graph.

In [25]:
#arima model
import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error
import math
from colorama import Fore  # For colored output

def arima_model(y_train, y_valid, order=(2,1,0), forecast_steps=5):
    # Fit ARIMA model
    model = sm.tsa.arima.ARIMA(y_train, order=order)
    fitted_model = model.fit()

    # Forecast with ARIMA
    y_pred = fitted_model.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)

    # Calculate metrics
    score_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_valid, y_pred)
    score_rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_valid, y_pred))
    score_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_valid - y_pred) / y_valid)) * 100
    
    # Print model summary and metrics
    print(fitted_model.summary())
    print(Fore.GREEN + 'RMSE: {}'.format(score_rmse))
    print(Fore.GREEN + 'MAE: {}'.format(score_mae))
    print(Fore.GREEN + 'MAPE: {}'.format(score_mape))
    
    return fitted_model

SARIMA function¶

There are four seasonal elements that are not part of ARIMA that must be configured; they are: SARIMA(p,d,q)(P,D,Q)SeasonalOrders

P: Seasonal autoregressive order.

D: Seasonal difference order.

Q: Seasonal moving average order.

m: The number of time steps for a single seasonal period. For example, an S of 12 for monthly data suggests a yearly seasonal cycle.

In [26]:
def sarimax_model(y_train, y_valid, order=(2, 1, 0), seasonal_order=(1, 0, 0, 12), forecast_steps=66):
    # Fit SARIMA model
    model = sm.tsa.SARIMAX(y_train, order=order, seasonal_order=seasonal_order)
    fitted_model = model.fit()

    # Forecast with SARIMA
    y_pred = fitted_model.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)

    # Calculate metrics
    score_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_valid, y_pred)
    score_rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_valid, y_pred))
    score_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_valid - y_pred) / y_valid)) * 100

    # Print model summary and metrics
    print(fitted_model.summary())
    print(Fore.GREEN + 'RMSE: {}'.format(score_rmse))
    print(Fore.GREEN + 'MAE: {}'.format(score_mae))
    print(Fore.GREEN + 'MAPE: {}'.format(score_mape))

    return fitted_model

Model evaluation using auto arima¶

A model that fits the data very well while using lots of features will be assigned a larger AIC score than a model that uses fewer features to achieve the same goodness-of-fit.

Therefore, we are interested in finding the model that yields the lowest AIC value using auto arima.

The auro_arima function works by conducting differencing tests (i.e., KwiatkowskiPhillipsSchmidtShin, Augmented Dickey-Fuller or PhillipsPerron) to determine the order of differencing, d, and then fitting models within ranges of defined start_p, max_p, start_q, max_q ranges.

In [27]:
from pmdarima.arima import auto_arima

def fit_auto_arima(y_train,d=0,D=0):
    # Use auto_arima to find the best SARIMA model order
    auto_a = auto_arima(y_train, trace=True, error_action='ignore', test='adf',m=12,D=D,d=d,
                        seasonal=True, stepwise=True,
                        suppress_warnings=True)
    
    # Print the summary of the best SARIMA model
    print(auto_a.summary())
    
    return auto_a

Rolling forecast¶

In [28]:
#for arima models

A rolling forecast is where we forecast one step ahead and then refit our model on the new data, adding data from the test set. This means that early deviations from the time series because of the trend won't hurt our ability to forecast future steps.

In [29]:
def rolling_forecast(train, test,model):
    history = [x for x in train]
    predictions = []
    results = {}
    yhat = model.forecast()[0]

    predictions.append(yhat)
    history.append(test[0])
    for i in range(1, len(test)):
        yhat = model.forecast()[0]
        predictions.append(yhat)
        obs = test[i]
        history.append(obs)
    mse = mean_squared_error(test, predictions)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(test, predictions)
    rmse = math.sqrt(mse)
    predictions = pd.Series(predictions, index=test.index)
    results['predictions'] = predictions
    results['mse'] = mse
    results['rmse'] = rmse
    results['mae'] = mae
    return results

Walk forward forecast¶

Assess model's performance on new, unseen data.

In [30]:
#for sarima models
In [31]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
from math import sqrt

def walk_forecast(train, valid,order=(7,1,0),seasonal_order=(7,1,0,12)):
    history = [x for x in train]
    predictions = list()

    for t in range(len(valid)):
        model = sm.tsa.SARIMAX(history, order=order, seasonal_order=seasonal_order)
        model_fit = model.fit()

        output = model_fit.forecast()
        yhat = output[0]

        predictions.append(yhat)
        obs = valid[t]
        history.append(obs)

        print('predicted=%f, expected=%f' % (yhat, obs))

    rmse = sqrt(mean_squared_error(valid, predictions))
    print('Test RMSE: %.3f' % rmse)

    plt.title('Forecast')
    plt.plot(valid, label='Actual')
    plt.plot(valid.index, predictions, color='red', label='Predicted', ls='--')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

SARIMA¶

Blue region is set to 95% confidence interval spikes above the blue region suggests that there is a correlation

The autocorrelation function (ACF): It shows the correlation between consumption versus the lagged versions of itself.

The partial autocorrelation (PACF): It shows the correlation between the consumption versus the lagged version excluding the effects of earlier lags, for example, it show the effective influence of the lag 3 in the current temperatures excluding the effects of the lags 1 and 2.

A higher order autoregressive term in the data. Use the partial autocorrelation function to determine the order of the autoregressive term. May be cuts off at 3rd lag AR(4)/AR(6)

VAR¶

Capture dependencies and interactions between variables over time

In [60]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import grangercausalitytests
#determines whether one time series is useful in forecasting another
def grangers_causation_matrix(data, variables, test='ssr_chi2test', verbose=False):    
    df = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((len(variables), len(variables))), columns=variables, index=variables)
    for c in df.columns:
        for r in df.index:
            test_result = grangercausalitytests(data[[r, c]], maxlag=12, verbose=False)
            p_values = [round(test_result[i+1][0][test][1],4) for i in range(12)]
            if verbose: print(f'Y = {r}, X = {c}, P Values = {p_values}')
            min_p_value = np.min(p_values)
            df.loc[r, c] = min_p_value
    df.columns = [var + '_x' for var in variables]
    df.index = [var + '_y' for var in variables]
    return df
